Follow-Up Module

Deterministic retry orchestration for human-dependent workflows.

This module does not “send reminder emails.”

It governs temporal accountability.

If this module behaves unpredictably, your system quietly loses trust — not through crashes, but through silence.

Core Principle

Time is a domain constraint.
Retries must be bounded.
Follow-up must be deterministic.

Reminders are not UX sugar.

They are enforcement of incomplete obligations.

Configuration Surface
export const followupConfig = {
checkIntervalHours: 24,
maxAttempts: 3,
retryDelayHours: 48,
timezone: "Africa/Accra",
email: {
provider: "sendgrid",
apiKey: process.env.SENDGRID_API_KEY ?? "",
from: process.env.FOLLOWUP_FROM ?? "noreply@postwins.com",
},
} as const;

This config encodes policy, not infrastructure.

Each field carries architectural meaning.

Temporal Governance
checkIntervalHours

How often the system scans for pending obligations.

This should align with:

Worker scheduler frequency

Cron cadence

Job queue polling interval

Mismatch creates phantom delays.

If worker runs hourly but interval is 24h, you are computing wastefully.

If worker runs daily but interval is 1h, you are lying to yourself.

maxAttempts

Bounded retry policy.

Prevents:

Infinite notification loops

Silent spam escalation

Governance erosion

After max attempts, escalation should occur — not silence.

Escalation is a domain decision, not an email decision.

retryDelayHours

Backoff policy.

This defines when the next attempt becomes eligible.

It must not depend on worker timing alone.

The next attempt time must be stored in the database.

Never infer next eligibility purely from attempt count.

Time-based systems must be stateful.

timezone

Critical.

Scheduling based on UTC alone causes:

Off-hour notifications

Compliance violations

Cultural friction

Time is political.

If this system operates in Ghana, “Africa/Accra” is correct.

Never default to server timezone.

Never trust container timezone.

Always make timezone explicit.

Email Provider Boundary
email: {
provider: "sendgrid",
apiKey: process.env.SENDGRID_API_KEY ?? "",
from: process.env.FOLLOWUP_FROM ?? "noreply@postwins.com",
}

This is infrastructure configuration.

It must remain outside domain logic.

Domain code should call:

sendFollowupNotification(...)

Not:

sendgrid.send(...)

Provider coupling belongs in an adapter layer.

The domain should not care whether the message is sent via:

SendGrid

SES

SMTP

Internal queue

WhatsApp

SMS

Infrastructure changes.
Governance remains.

Required Structural Guarantees (Implied)

Even though not shown here, a production follow-up system must persist:

target entity ID

attempt count

lastAttemptAt

nextEligibleAt

status (PENDING | COMPLETED | EXHAUSTED)

tenantId

Without these:

You cannot guarantee retry determinism.

Determinism Requirements

A follow-up engine must be:

Idempotent

Retry-safe

Multi-worker safe

Tenant isolated

Clock drift tolerant

Never rely on in-memory counters.

Never rely on job scheduler memory.

All attempt state must live in the database.

Concurrency Considerations

If multiple workers scan concurrently:

Use row-level locking

Or atomic update where nextEligibleAt <= now

Or SELECT … FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED

Without locking, you risk double-sends.

Double-sends destroy trust faster than missed sends.

Failure Modes to Design For

Email provider timeout
→ Do not increment attempt unless send confirmed

Worker crash mid-send
→ Must not mark as completed prematurely

Timezone misalignment
→ Schedule drift across DST changes

API key missing
→ Fail fast at startup, not silently

maxAttempts reached
→ Must transition to EXHAUSTED state explicitly

Observability Expectations

Every attempt should produce:

structured log

correlation ID

tenantId

attempt number

success/failure outcome

provider response metadata (if safe)

Silence is not observability.

Scalability Considerations

For large tenant counts:

Partition follow-up table by tenant

Index nextEligibleAt

Avoid full-table scans

Batch process eligible rows

Time-based systems scale with indexing discipline.

Security Considerations

API keys must never leak into logs

from address must be controlled

Follow-up content must not leak internal IDs

Tenant isolation must be enforced before send

Reminder systems are subtle data exfiltration vectors.

Mental Model

Think of this module as a clock-driven compliance engine.

It asks:

Who owes the system a response?
Have we reminded them?
Have we done so fairly?
Have we stopped after reasonable effort?

The difference between a chaotic SaaS and a trusted one
often lies in how it handles unfinished obligations.

Time is a first-class domain constraint.

Treat it that way.
